Predicting MOOC Completion from Early Engagement Patterns

Analysis of FutureLearn Cyber Security Course Data

Nepoliyan Ria

January 16, 2026

Executive Summary

This report analyzes seven runs of the FutureLearn MOOC Cyber Security: Safety at Home, Online, and in Life using two CRISP-DM cycles to test whether early engagement predicts course completion.

Key findings

  • Completion rate: 5.8%
  • Activation rate: 56.3%
  • Week 1 predictor: High Week 1 engagers (75% complete) reach 26.2% completion vs.0.1% for very low engagers
  • Practical threshold: Flag learners completing <40% of Week 1 by day 7

Introduction

Dataset

Seven runs of the course:

  • Enrolments: 37,296
  • Step interactions: 423,072

Research question

Can early-course engagement predict whether learners complete a MOOC?

Key takeaways (Cycle 1)

  • 43.7% of enrolled learners never activate.
  • Engagement is bimodal (early dropouts vs.persisters).
  • Most dropout happens in Weeks 13.

Cycle 2: Week 1 engagement as predictor

Week 1 distribution

Distribution of Week 1 engagement levels

Completion by Week 1 engagement level

Completion rate increases with Week 1 engagement

Completion Rates by Week 1 Engagement Level
Week 1 Engagement N Completion Rate
Very Low 7587 0.1%
Low 4060 0.7%
Medium 1557 2.8%
High 7561 26.2%

Key takeaways (Cycle 2)

  • Completion increases monotonically with Week 1 engagement.
  • A practical early-warning threshold is <40% Week 1 completion.

Overall conclusions

Week 1 engagement is a strong early indicator of MOOC completion. Learners completing 75% of Week 1 achieve a completion rate of 26.2% versus 0.1% for very low engagers.

Flagging learners below 40% Week 1 completion by day 7 supports timely, targeted intervention.
